# (1) present-day patterns in GHG emissions (which regions/countries/economic sectors are the biggest emitters? Which emit the least?)

# look at what entity has the highest and lowest emissions, which year has the highest and lowest emissions, and which sector has the highest and lowest emissions


entity_emission <- sectors %>% 
  filter(year >= 2000, entity != "World") %>% 
  group_by(entity) %>% 
  summarize( total = sum(co2, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(desc(total)) 
  
 
  df <- entity_emission %>% 
    head(10)
  
  
ggplot(data = df, aes(x = entity, y = (total/1000000000)))+
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity')+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))+
  labs(title = "Top Ten Greenhouse Gas Emitters", x = "Country", y = "Total Emissions in Billions", subtitle = "From 2000-2018")

df2 <- entity_emission %>% 
  tail(10)

ggplot(data = df2, aes(x = entity, y = (total/1000000)))+
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity')+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))+
  labs(title = "Bottom Ten Greenhouse Gas Emitters", x = "Country", y = "Total Emissions in Millions", subtitle = "From 2000-2018")

# (2) long-term trends in carbon emissions over time (globally, country-by-county, and sector-by-sector);

# longterm trends in the top five countries over time

carb_over_time <- sectors %>% 
  filter(entity != "World") %>% 
  group_by(entity, year) %>% 
  summarize( total = sum(co2, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(desc(total)) 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'entity'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
carbs <- carb_over_time %>% 
  filter(entity %in% c("United States", "China", "India", "Russia", "European Union (27)")) 

ggplot(data = carbs, aes(x = year, y = (total/1000000000), color = entity))+
  geom_line()+
  labs(title = "Longterm Trends in Carbon Emissions", subtitle = "In the Top 5 Emitting Countries", x = "Years", y = 'Emissions in Billions', color = "Countries")+
  scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 16)+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

Results

For the first question, I decided to display the top ten greenhouse gas emitters and then the bottom ten as well, not including countries that had no data available. For the second question, I charted the top five greenhouse gas emitters across the years that we have data for.
